<font color="#FF0000">FOR HONOR AND FOR HER</font><br>
<tt>Wed Feb 19  0:25:03 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Del thought this would be another appropriate site for this poem.  I'll give a bit more history than I did at the other site (#44) where this is also posted.  My third grade teacher was Lucile Wardell, from Salem, Oregon.  She was a wonderful person, and one of the two teachers I was able to continue to communicate with while in the service, and yes, while in Vietnam.  Ms. Eva Wolf was the other; she passed away last year.  <br><br>
Mrs. Wardell was, and is, one of the kindest, gentlist persons I have had the pleasure to know.  What I didn't know is that her husband was killed when his B-17 had to ditch at sea after a bombing raid into Germany during WW II.  He was in the Eighth Air Force, stationed in England.  The Eighth Air Force had a reunion in 1991, and she went to England to particpate.  She returned with momentos of the trip, and one was a card from a service many years previous. On the card was the following poem.  I took it and added to it my own interpretation:<br><br>
For Honor And For Her<br><br>
Somewhere a woman, thrusting fear away,<br>
Faces the future bravely for your sake;<br>
Toils on from dawn 'till dark, from day to day;<br>
Fights back her tears, nor heeds the bitter ache;<br>
She loves you, trusts you, breaths in prayer your name;<br>
Soil not her faith in you by sin or shame.<br><br>
Somewhere a woman watches--filled with pride;<br>
Shrined in her heart, you share a place with none;<br>
She toils, she waits, she prays, 'till side by side<br>
You stand together when the battle's done.<br>
Oh keep for her dear sake a shameless name;<br>
Bring back to her a manhood free from shame.<br><br>
--M. Scruton<br>
From the Morning Worship Service<br>
Rev. Dolman, Rector<br>
Church of England<br>
Sunday, August 22, 1943<br><br>
A Post Script<br>
by John C. Ratliff, August 7, 1992<br><br>
I have seen war, some twenty-seven years later,<br>
After this poem had been lost to our services.<br>
Oh, how I wish some of my fellow servicemen<br>
Could have seen it, felt it, been shamed by it.<br><br>
Our war was different in many ways,<br>
A country far away, a culture so vastly different;<br>
A political climate which seemed tos state<br>
That we were the bad guys, not they.<br><br>
But there were some of us who knew,<br>
The difference between responsibility<br>
And the same word with an &quot;ir&quot; prefix;<br>
Who knew that no matter what happened, we still lived   ultimately with ourselves.<br><br>
So let us hope that this poem can form a base, where again service people will know<br>
That they are not alone, that people still love them, and that they have honor, and duty<br>
To fulfill, so that our country can continue to shine the light of freedom ot other peoples.<br><br>
________<br><br>
Mrs. Wardell sent this poem to her English members, and they published it in their newsletter.  I have a copy with graphics, nicely layed out, that I will send to anyone who requests it.<br><br>
By the way, we all need to be in touch with our grade school teachers; along the way, they have done a lot for us.  Thank you Mrs. Wardell.<br><br>
 
